Pattern: 3 Two Separate Structures (Array Parallel Processing)
1. The Interview Triggers
* Evaluating intersections, differences, or combinations across two distinct collections.
*. Merging, joining, or validating sub-sequence properties between strings or arrays.

2. Core Mechanics
Assign one standalone pointer to each separate array or string (p1 = 0, p2 = 0). Move each pointer independently based on the comparison of the elements they are targeting.

3. Production Java Blueprint
public List<Integer> twoArraysTemplate(int[] arr1, int[] arr2) {
    List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
    int p1 = 0;
    int p2 = 0;
    
    // Loop only while BOTH pointers are safely inside bounds
    while (p1 < arr1.length && p2 < arr2.length) {
        if (arr1[p1] < arr2[p2]) {
            p1++;
        } else if (arr1[p1] > arr2[p2]) {
            p2++;
        } else {
            result.add(arr1[p1]); // Common element identified
            p1++;
            p2++;
        }
    }
    
    // Optional: Clean-up loops if trailing elements must be processed
    while (p1 < arr1.length) { /* process arr1 */ p1++; }
    while (p2 < arr2.length) { /* process arr2 */ p2++; }
    
    return result;
}

4. Corner Cases & Interview Pitfalls
Asymmetric Lengths: One list will naturally terminate before the second one. If you use an && condition inside your main while statement, ensure you handle remaining elements in your trailing logic arrays if the problem statement requires full coverage (like Merge Sorted Array).

5. Essential Interview Questions
Easy: LeetCode 88 - Merge Sorted Array, LeetCode 392 - Is Subsequence
Medium: LeetCode 986 - Interval List Intersections, LeetCode 844 - Backspace String Compare
